FBIS3-5705 "dreas047_c_94002" FBIS-EAS-94-047 Document Type:Daily Report 10 Mar 1994 North Korea 7, 8 March U.S.-ROK `War' Exercises Reported SK1003043194 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0418 GMT 10 Mar 94 SK1003043194 Pyongyang KCNA Language: English Article Type:BFN [Text] Pyongyang, March 10 (KCNA) -- The U.S. imperialists on March 8 brought two Okinawa-based KC-135 tanker planes to the sky above South Korea to stage a war exercise against the northern half of Korea, refueling in mid air at night some twenty fighter-bombers and assault planes including F-16s and A-10s belonging to the U.S. Air Force present in South Korea, according to military sources. On the same day, some 10 large cargo planes based in the U.S. mainland and the Pacific airlifted a large aggression force and combat equipment to the U.S. Air Force bases in Osan and Kunsan. And an Okinawa-based RC-135 strategic reconnaissance plane, flying above the area of the military demarcation line, committed photographing and electronic reconnaissance on the strategic in- depth areas of the North. On March 7, puppet army ground units ran amok in a war exercise in Yonchon and Paju counties, firing shells and large-calibre machinegun bullets.
